      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000063013,
      "SummaryText": "Also, the Plant will receive 6,000 gallon tanker trucks alternatively delivering approximately 19.5 percent and approximately 30 percent aqueous ammonia, since the manufacturer does not produce 24 percent aqueous ammonia.  As a result, the Plant is required to develop and submit to the U.S. EPA, per 40 CFR 68, a Risk Management Plan (RMP) since aqueous ammonia at a 20 percent or greater concentration will be stored in a 40,000 gallon AST that exceeds the threshold storage limit of 20,000 gallons as stipulated in Table 1 of 40 CFR 68.130.\r\n\r\n\u00bf\tFive-Year Accident History\r\n\r\nThe Plant has had no accidents, including spills, associated with the operation of the 40,000 gallon aqueous ammonia AST in the last five years.  The tank was commissioned in March 2011.\r\n\r\n\u00bf\tAccidental Release Prevention And Emergency Response Policies\r\n\r\nThe Plant maintains the following prevention and emergency response plans:\r\n\r\n1.\tContingency Plan (for hazardous waste generated episodically)\r\n2.\tEmergency Response and Disaster Control Plan\r\n3.\tSpill Prevention, Control, and Countermeasures (SPCC) Plan\r\n\r\nThe Plant episodically generates refractory material which is classified as a hazardous.  As a result, the Plant is required to develop a Contingency Plan and to implement the Contingency Plan during a fire, explosion, or hazardous waste release (COMAR 26.13.03.05(E)).  The Contingency Plan was developed based on requirements found in 40 CFR 262.34(a)(4); 40 CFR 265 Subpart D; the Code of Maryland Regulations (COMAR) 26.13.05.02 General Facility Standards; COMAR 26.13.05.03 Preparedness and Prevention; and COMAR 26.13.05.04 Contingency Plan and Emergency Procedures.  Also included in the Contingency Plan are additional requirements outlined in 40 CFR 262.34(d)(5)(i).\r\n\r\nAs part of preparing the Contingency Plan, the Plant also developed an Emergency Response and Disaster Control Plan that describes the actions that will be taken in the case of small or large fires, explosions, sudden or non-"
    },
